A Republican Strategy to Oppose Obama’s Reelection
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by affirming that electoral fraud is less common in the US than the number of people killed by lightning.
The Republican lawyers have, by the way, only recorded 300 cases of electoral fraud in the US in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for the conduct of elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have promulgated new laws that make the process of registration or ballot more difficult.
This phenomenon has gained in importance after the November 2010 elections, with 675 new Republican representatives recorded in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time limits for early voting, invalidate the right to register as voters on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court file is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the last two years, they have been promoting bills in 34 states that force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of Afro-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are regarded as voters who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs, who choose more for the Republican side, to use the tickets issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws demanding voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic voices.
For it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections have helped to register some 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of new voters registered in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were Afro-Americans, although they make up only 13% of the state's voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, whites, representing 76% of voters, made up only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Advocate General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the passed laws and see them as a clear goal of influencing the results in the key states for 2012.
A report by the Brennan Center in 2011 shows that those states that have passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral panel to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
