The Higgs boson analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a certain sensation last summer, and for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but not yet observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still missing to be completely secure.
Nevertheless, let's assume that it's actually the Higgs, because there seems to be a low risk of being deceived, and let's look at what it's all about.
There is an inevitable law in this world, which means that two objects cannot be present in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and do not try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that for it, too, such a law applies: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantity state", whereby this "state" consists, by and large, of some of their properties.
From this point of view, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a vicious gang of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley laboratories (which is absolutely amazing by the way): the mesons, which we will not treat here and the "force particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it has to be stressed here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly in this place, like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbing" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disturbed" so that this boson shows up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little like a frozen pond whose surface could only be shattered by a very large rock.
That's why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is helpful again to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a piece of paper would never keep on its own at the refrigerator.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (such as the photon) have no mass.
What can all these researches be "good" for, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine all the differences between the observations and the predictions of the SM in detail.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who are keenly hoping that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has major shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (renewed ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there are none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous-line laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially regarded as a "laboratory plaything".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras around the world and awarded him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With its Committee on Death in Dignity, Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate will have to be resumed shortly, even though a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the palliative care home of Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to be helped with the food.
He even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' home.
Returning to childhood is unacceptable humiliation for certain persons.
"That depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards," he notes.
For according to several people who work in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these retrograde steps.
Patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who take care of them no longer overburden them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But the illness really made me know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more desires in life," she says before accepting that she should be put on a mask to help her breathe.
She still expects a last visit of her son, who comes from Italy, in the next few days.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers offer body care and food support.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if you take into account that one day we'll all die.
Here, life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or pepsi according to his wishes.
Diabetic patients no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," reports Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
Victor-Gadbois's home isn't a day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family reunion in the yard and is well supported by his pillows while in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel, worried.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois' home come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal area, are more or less exclusively specializing in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that causes a number of palliative care specialists to look forward to the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide with concern.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care personalities such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's healthcare system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before they are accepted to go to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room with great pain for 14 days without taking measures to relieve her.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients bitterly until the last day despite the worst predictions.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped an arduous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she told me that she was sorry that I gave up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not accepting this request after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent during pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care for the Montreal community, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in the patient being put to sleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly be able to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated, all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be eased."
