A Constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever with regard to the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited authority, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this assembly two additional months to complete its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a preliminary text, which has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "stepping the law."
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians section by section.
It is also a way for the President to regain his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest rages throughout the country.
After confirming in an interview with American newsreel Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "You either vote for my draft or I retain unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 largely Islamist members of this constituent assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not complied with the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away, believing that they were unable to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities and civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that most of the articles were adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed at the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the constituent assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made it possible to apply them more strictly.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Holyness" is reciprocated by the liberals, who regard it only as a propaganda strike.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, since "the people who are asked to give an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
One can see here the first signs of a theocracy".
Liberal fears are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"Currently, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics, some of whom have been trained in the French system," appeases Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, that "with regard to Article 220, there may be ambiguity, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have called for.
The latter also share their fears about the text, which they regard as threatening freedom.
The situation of blasphemy is maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no more article refers to the protection of women, stressed Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on TV last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel Ukrainian tourists await holy places, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
To bow before the holy places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, the walking on the water, the stilling of the sea storm and fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
However, most of the sanctuaries are in Jerusalem.
Believers here follow the path of the Passion or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path starts at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the church of the tomb on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
This is, according to the Christian view, the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in A.D. 70.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes there with wishes that then come true.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in A.D. 25.
They lie on a rock face in the mountains at a height of 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters, is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the mountaintop.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There are ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in caves in the Judean desert, as well as some 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures by the visitors and bath servants of the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the memorial to the children, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the lands in which they died resound.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
Israel's three main recreational areas lie on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salinity and thus even carries non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and medicinal mud as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of stressed nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia ran through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
Tradition has it that Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, which are named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is said to be the hold of all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo events.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed today.
Tourist watch list
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the journey is better taken with you in no euros, but in dollars, which can simply be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a expressway and in Haifa the only underground line of the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
Actually, it's an underground funicular.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which includes a change for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you can choose between different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this there are many well-fed cats, who wander comfortably and unmolested through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an additional 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recovery seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on 9 February 2011.
"The big and powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money on language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already acting with fake certificates
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families that remain in their homeland.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to pass a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail trade.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests are to become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
Not only language tests, but also tests must be put into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be proven both for obtaining and renewing the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The total number of examination places will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the representatives of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law entered into force in the press: What is the point of all this?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring about, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
In particular, speakers from the Migration Authority replied, the aim was to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, Head of the Representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, under the pretext of helping him, will put him in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his like months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
Many complaints from our migrants reach us.
"In the homeland you are promised one thing, and on arrival you will be deceived, your passports will be taken and you will not receive the promised salary," confirms Tolib Schwaripov, Head of the Labour Migration Department of the Tajik Migration Authority.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they are not only unable to speak the language of the target country, but also cannot express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school clothes.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect with regard to the law.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to reside illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "forbidden entry for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A falsified registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
Russian police personnel know that our documents are mostly forged and we are not registered, and then there are cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says Tajike Umed Hushkadamov to journalists.
"Just don't shy away from the costs of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be falsified.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by staff of the Federal Migration Authority.
The forged papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for nothing: every migrant who hoped to be able to spare himself tests thus paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that certificates cannot be bought easily.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time they get time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Ministry of Interior ignores illegal arms market
Very low proportion of legal weapons in criminal offences
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning to tighten up the weapons law for private weapons owners.
The authorities are reacting to recent events: injured in wedding shootings and seven dead in the rampage of Moscow lawyer Dmitri Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the use of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would shortly be submitted to the Duma.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - call on the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal justice officer, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed during six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
According to the authors, any weapon for little money can be found in Moscow.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel are illegal weapons stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen both from police armory and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Many military camps often experienced explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson in order to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, weapons manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore squander arms under the hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," reports the expert.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is its own, sometimes artisanal production, as well as a mafia that organizes smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share each of the five channels has of the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Public Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminal literature and publicly available data on arms portals.
According to investigators, most of the illegal weapons come from the army and legal protection authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market were there because of the "guilt of those responsible for their work with weapons," says the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict areas, 14% come from theft of weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun store, who does not want to be named, assures that weapons found during illegal excavations have long since been bought by no one, because they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get supplies in a weapons warehouse.
An Ensign buys a weapon, such as a TT-type pistol.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police know everything, of course, and therefore, if they are unable to comply with the crime detection plan, they periodically make control purchases from traders who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find each other through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested to come to the "Begovaya" station, where a person would be waiting for me to take me to a certain place where we could negotiate the price.
The prize for the weapon I only learned there
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"In order to get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," the sales consultant says. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but there it is necessary to go and arrange with a code like "by Ivan Ivanovich, who tells that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I'm even getting a couple of rings right now about a friend I trust.
He also gives me the rings because he knows that I don't rat him out.
Newbies are looking for weapons in different ways.
