Fast food and supermarket workers strike in the US
One in four U.S. youths sits behind Mc Donald's till at some point
In recent days, there have been massive protests across the US against low wages in stores of Walmart and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will swell further or whether they will soon run out of air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organisations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of simple Walmart and fast-food workers, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of founding trade unions.
So far, this sector of the economy has hardly been organised as a trade union.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, on Black Friday, where sales took place in the US, attracting millions of customers, which sometimes led to hand-held crowds.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their work and, together with trade unions and left-wing activists, struck branches of the chain whose target group is low- and middle-income people.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
On average, the goods in the Walmart stores are between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
Therefore, many of Walmart's low-paid employees buy only at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart can often only sell the goods so cheaply because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklifts or hand scanners.
The participants in the Black Friday protests demanded wage increases and expressed their anger at the fact that the contribution to in-house health insurance had increased from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 per hour could not afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from California University in Berkeley prove that if the company raised the average wage to 12 dollars an hour, it would cost Walmart 3.2 billion dollars.
That's about 1.1% more than they're now donating for pay.
If Walmart completely transferred the wage increases to the customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
For them this would be an increase of only $12.39 per year compared to today.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that protests have only occurred in nine states and that they have not caused any loss to the company.
The Black Friday lasted the next day in its shop from 8 o'clock in the evening on Thursday to midnight, and during this period Walmart sold about 5000 items per second.
In total, the Walmart-Kassen on "Black Friday" carried out almost 100 million transactions.
In an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post, the company's spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed that a total of "less than five" Walmart employees dropped out of work and that the protest action was just "another PR trick" of the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their goal was not Walmart stores (which are not wanted in this progressive city and therefore so far nonexistent), but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's says the company is selling billions of portions, and yet you're not being granted sick days, and you're not getting paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour according to federal and New York legislation.
In fast food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too strong, and on average, their simple employees in New York get $8.90 an hour.
No one in this expensive city earns less than she does.
How it is possible to get along with so little money in New York is incomprehensible to me.
There was once a time when almost a quarter of all U.S. youths were behind the bar at McDonald's after school, but the youths still lived with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw it as the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald's employees, I constantly meet people who complain that they get along with this salary and sometimes even have to feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the Forum of the Wall Street Journal, whose author notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began on Thursday at 6:30 a.m. in front of McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and chefs of fast-food restaurants receive a minimum wage of $15 per hour, which is more than a doubling of the current minimum wage.
They continued to call for the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
The U.S. law prohibits corporate governance from standing in the way of this goal and admonishing or dismissing union members.
On the other hand, corporate governance doesn't make it easy for them.
The establishment of trade unions in the fast food industry is difficult for objective reasons.
The most important reason is the high turnover of personnel.
Dissatisfied
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The highlight of the protests was a meeting at noon in front of McDonald's in Times Square, where some local Democrats spoke, including City Councillor Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says it's selling billions of portions, and yet you won't get sick days, and you won't get paid for your honest work!"
The demonstrators were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should work together to support fast food workers so that they can get a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!"
According to The New York Times, this was the largest of its kind in the history of the US fast food industry.
However, only a few hundred people were on site, of whom not all are employed in the fast food industry, where tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet clear whether the spark of these protests will mobilize entire masses.
"The brain is only moderately outsmarted so far"
The theme of expanded reality, popular among followers of modern technologies, has been commonly perceived by the lens of special glasses lately.
First Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it became known that Microsoft had also filed a patent.
In a conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear, however, that the glasses were only a transit station for the company's scientists.
It excites the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to expand the limits of this interaction.
So far, mankind has largely been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to anticipate 5-10 years and anticipate the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What more can we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, many things still play out on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) has been improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We try to change that, work on real three-dimensional imaging systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much easier.
And first of all, let's get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- I'm sure it's not the all-purpose solution, because it raises questions about privacy, because you don't always want to inform everyone by about your actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project where we experimented with short and concise gestures instead of sweeping gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that registered the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gestures and language.
- How so?
For example, we'd like to ask you to hand you this bubble can?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and can't afford at the time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the development of new types of sensors that allow us to capture reactions from people more precisely.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer a good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What demands do you make on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or anything else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional detection.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixel itself, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Seen in this way, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the X- and the Y-, but also along the Z-axis must be taken into account.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
Man's movements are extremely dynamic and, frankly, the current 30 fps are too little, especially for gestures.
In our laboratory in Redmond, Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor with a controllable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between man and machine.
For my work I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem as more calculations would be needed.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera angles to see how this helps us to determine a position three-dimensionally.
- If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that, with regard to the application of technology of advanced reality in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in your uplifted hand on the road, but I think the most amazing option would be a "changing" expanded reality, in which we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and that is their strength (only you can see privates), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality by means of glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
Let us imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point to: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that expanded reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She's very sensitive to pressure!
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is at the moment as weak as someone blows over the ball of hands.
There are also wrist bands that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outwit the brain?
Make it think it feels what it should feel when it sees something right now?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried yet.
Here is another task that we will have to deal with for a long time to come, namely to let a person who is physically in a closed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms and large balls.
So far, the brain is only moderately outsmarted, and there are still many busy years ahead of us.
This is exactly what makes working in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: We are only at the beginning of many topics.
