Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with earth-dwellers on board embark on a search for a replacement planet.
In order to save mankind, the important question arises as to how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
I do not think there are many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"This is Mars and Venus," says the scientific assistant of the Astronomical Sternberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, on the surface of Venus there is a temperature of 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, in space.
The researchers first looked at the question of procreation in space in terms of flora.
Half a century before, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from the terrestrial species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent to space to investigate how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
A normal chick is developing.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find a foothold; it must be able to stand on its legs and begin to move," explains Vladimir Sychev, head of the Laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
Without a solid surface, the chicks turned wild.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later, they just died.
"We let chicks slip twice and then set the whole thing up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev notes about the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, on the biosatellite "Bion" only same-sex species will be found.
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized and sent into space.
In principle, nothing special was noted.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but once again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, man could do that in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was with Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on earth could have answered the following question: Will she survive the space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawitzkaja, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Still, there's a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, where everything went well after long flights and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even when flying into orbit," concludes Kosmonaut Valeri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet mankind must seek new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and artificial gravity.
The hydro laboratory in the cosmonaut preparation centre is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Although adults find water to be pleasant, it is a strange environment; yet infants feel water to be a natural element.
It's as if the little Ichtyanders were testifying that life on the land descended from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the mother's belly for about 9 months in the amniotic fluid, and the fact that it is easier to get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swim only 2 weeks pass.
"This is too little time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
Thus, while weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman cannot do without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles regress tremendously quickly and thus the ability to push the child out decreases.
All right, let's get around this with birth-seeking aids.
The birth could also take place, for example, in a special chamber to squeeze out the child.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the gravity, the organism cannot train the skeleton and the muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in orbit like an adult for training in a stress suit.
He will simply lack what is of fundamental importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely inappropriate person," says Igor Pestov, head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it becomes reality when the Earth's inhabitants in their spaceships set out to become a distant planet that will be the home for their descendants born in space.
NKÚ chief: Control of the black system fails due to political faults
The Czech Republic has good supervisory bodies and adequate laws in connection with public contracts, but falls behind in their application.
Speaking for Aktuálně.cz, the Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Office (Nejvy
"A law is never perfect, but it needs to be applied correctly - and I do not think that is the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
