As a negative example of practice, he cites Prime Minister Petr Nečas' attitude to the so-called "black system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls - is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply be the head of the government, and the supervisory authority, whose duty is to monitor compliance with the law, hinders its activity," notes Kala.
At the meeting of the Committee on Control of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries concerning public contracts were compared.
What was that specific about?
This is a parallel test that we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, it is a question of the European legislature defining how public contracts should be managed, on which national legislation is based, and finally, there is the actual practical application.
We have compared all of this with each other, and although the examination has not yet been completed, we have found very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "stricter and more perfect" for us, but the actual application is better in some parameters in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to establish new and more precise rules over and over again. One must also deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What results from this project?
It is precisely this kind of joint control that could help us to stop constantly trying to perfect laws and reduce and level thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Profitability means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But the lowering of thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we will achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we only burden the system with excessive "paper stuff", and those who seek gaps in the system have made it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
They talk about the problems involved in the practical implementation of the Czech Public Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Accounts, which is similar in structure to ours and also has a college which is only formed slightly differently. However, in principle both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also comparable to a certain extent, but Germany is a federal state, i.e. there are also these accounting offices in the individual federal states - in which the German system differs from ours.
The BRH is only allowed to control federal funds, which corresponds to our state resources.
Public funds, which are administered by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the state accounting authorities.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would hate to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, in some respects, Germany is often referred to as a model, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that perhaps because the examiners are better there?
Certainly not, but as I said, I do not like such comparisons.
It should also be noted that those countries that are an example to us are also facing problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have anything to do with our agency, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what importance did the amendment of the Procurement Act have for your authority, do you already feel any impact?
