As our controls take place retrospectively, we must expect a certain delay here.
So far, we are more likely to experience effects during the preparatory phase of future controls - for example, we have introduced the new control instrument "Recognition of Risks of Uneconomicity" and with this we have examined and analysed almost 14,000 public contracts - here the changes will naturally have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positive, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be complied with.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to scrutiny are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to ensure that any failure to comply with the award law amounts to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system only puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out of here?
First of all, let us say which path is not effective.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now prohibited or allowed?
After all, a law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply come to the head of the government, and the supervisory authority, whose duty is to monitor compliance with the law, can hinder its activity.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we pretend that nothing is.
The Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best bid is excluded solely because of formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I believe is missing from us.
