Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the Space Agency at a Council of Ministers meeting of member states of the European Space Agency (ESA). Poland is thus the second member of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008.
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's way into space began much earlier, of course.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were concerned with space travel, but they did not always come across understanding of it.
I would like to remind you, for example, of A. Šternfeld's lecture of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Entgang zur Kosmonautik".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's world-renowned contribution to the development of space travel was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925 a railway-draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project were unfortunately unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to brake the draisins.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with missile-powered missiles.
The research was carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents handed down that the research had progressed to the stage of practical tests.
The research was interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, a photoelectric hunting rocket was published in the specialist press by Ing. Rohoziński, and the following year, the work "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky was published.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work, its work ended from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society takes place in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the creation of a space company.
At the time, there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was foreseeable that space exploration would have a future.
Already in 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Federation of Space, which was founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member already in the autumn of 1956.
The following year the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice Chairman of the International Federation of Space.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum altitude of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests began with the two-stage rocket RM-2 in the B
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high-altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The first RM rocket was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the take-off weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed of this rocket (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport room with a capacity of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a takeoff weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
The repeal of the law on charitable work is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on charitable work.
This decision led to a lively public debate.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of labour (wages) there are price tensions.
This term refers to a situation in which the producer tries to compete economically by importing good products by "underselling" the competition in order to gain a greater market share and increase its profit.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to move their production abroad or buy it cheaply, or to give up their business.The result is high unemployment in countries with comparable high labour costs.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, public expenditure necessarily increases.
This situation is exacerbated by the fact that the entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage they cause to society as a whole.
This situation is well known, so that specific statistics are superfluous at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates in the individual economies a situation in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver their own population to private capital, regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in amendments to existing laws.
The aim of these measures is to force one's own population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the wage sector.
This is done on the one hand by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, and on the other hand by curtailing workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as increasing differences between rich and poor.
In Germany, for some years now, there have been public food outlets for poor people who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already going into the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regular cases in which employees receive such a low wage that the state has to increase its income to the minimum.
Such a scandal was also discovered in the case of auxiliary staff employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all the EU's southern states will undoubtedly lead to the same state in which people are forced to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level, or to suffer for a hunger wage on the fringes of society, hoping that at some point private investment capital will flow into the country.
Here the question naturally arises where this capital comes from?
When it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or capital is completely absent, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or Africa in general, employees work for a fraction of European wages.
This concerns all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media claim that the state must not participate with capital in its own economy, and that planned economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists narrowly on its view that the state must not intervene in the economy by directing it.
But then you have to ask yourself whether private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the whole state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer: Yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a practically all-powerful lobby, which is omnipresent in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual predominance, legislation in which virtually everything is criminal, but nothing is criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that a State Ministry, in the absence of finance, entrusts private legal entities closely associated with industry with the drafting of draft laws.
These draft laws are subsequently adopted in the Bundestag.
All violence then comes no longer from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Evidently, the liberal democracies are now quickly in a situation, as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic in Caesar's and Pompeius' times: "The state has long been in decline, and the offices have been filled with violence.
For bribes, by unlawful concealment of advantages or with stone and sword.
Corruption grew rampant, and the people went to vote with votes already bought" ... "People with character did not apply for office, so that the state did not have a consul for eight months as a result of this decline" ... "One really began to talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult situation was a single rule, and that a strong man had to be elected"... Appian thought of Pompeius, but the strong man was Caesar, who permanently replaced democracy with a single rule.
As it turns out, today's society, as in ancient times, is based on the ruthless preference of one's own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
By its very nature, private capital is not in a position to recognize and enforce the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, today and then, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites who are not at all seeking deeper reforms.
The cause of the rise of fascism and communism must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalisation of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today's point of view, the demise of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already emerging.
What is particularly disastrous is the fact that today's elites are completely ignorant of the possible future losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, of the humanitarian and social disasters we are already witnessing today, and of the crimes against humanity as we know them from older and more recent history.
The repeal of the law on charitable work is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under pressure from global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to push down the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political-social reforms that increase the state's participation in the economy, increase citizens' influence on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favour of the state.
