The movie Argo: When it's the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the US after the revolution, who had maintained the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have seriously damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to free the hostages only made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story, which gave the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the embassy was occupied, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, with an extravagant story helping them cover up their true identity - traveling with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff allegedly visiting locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by Tony Mendez, an exfiltration expert, also required Hollywood collaboration.
For the cover to become credible, articles about this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time it is also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
In this way the mood levels change in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic contemporary photographs, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the office corridors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the thriller Kein Kinderspiel (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller city without mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film that doesn't play in the director's home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that made the previous films of this director stand out from Hollywood's standard.
However, Affleck also proves this sense in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the initial sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story actually does not offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
However, he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes helping the reality a bit - which does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or the chase on the runway also seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have deserved more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some of its traction. It is a film that can be pursued with a certain interest and the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70th years.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of the omnipotent and omniscient secret services are.
Guidelines for inflating balloons, bananas and circuses
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which carries out an annual survey on the most absurd bank charges, decided this year to organise the competition "Absurdest regulation or idea from the EU workshop".
"This was the idea of the EU's recent plan to introduce a 40% female quota in the management of large European companies," said Patrik Nacher, who is responsible for organising this survey, to the Právo newspaper.
Among the nominated absurdities is, for example, the judgment of the European Court of Justice on the unification of insurance tariffs for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk for insurance companies.
"Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will take place until the end of February 2013", said Nacher.
One of the controversial EU regulations is the mandatory addition of bioethanol to fuels which, as a result, are harmful to nature, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain a relatively small amount of this dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs considerably more expensive this year.
Criticism in the past also reaped the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the sale ban for conventional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of this or that lobby from trade and industry, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more member states (for example, the Czech Republic is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks even with veto threats).
Lobby interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest commercial class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have a "curvature anomaly".
The European Commission defended itself with the argument that it only harmonises the inconsistent national standards that would hinder trade.
The standards on fruit and vegetables have already been softened by the EU against the resistance of some countries, pointing out that the previous directives would lead to a waste of food.
A candidate for victory in this survey may be the EU regulation of last year, which, according to balloons, must be provided with the indication that children under the age of eight may not inflate the balloon without the supervision of an adult.
The EU referred to an American study which, according to balloons, is the leading cause of child suffocation.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to 14 years of age when using fair sturds.
Curious ideas can also be found at home
A directive that concerns European officials themselves is also relatively absurd - anyone who takes an official role in the EU must not use the name Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the issue to Greece and must instead say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In cooperation with the Association of Liberal Economists Laissez Faire, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com nominated the above-mentioned absurdities as well as the EU regulation on the level of food stocks in the territory of a member country.
The EU thus set the maximum volume of food stocks that could be found in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
For example, the Czech Republic exceeded the fixed volume for canned mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a high fine.
The organisers of the survey were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or the idea of providing funding for applications for funding.
These ideas did not come from Brussels, of course, but from Prague.
"We are disadvantaged by the fact that we do not have a sea.
We will apply for a refund from the EU," said Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he argued that the grain harvest was very high and that the state warehouses were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
Since the Czech Republic has another way to seaports, according to Palas, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
Finally, the European Commission approached the Czech Republic to the extent that it organised an invitation to tender for the purchase of cereals from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The Ministry of Regional Development, led by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), offered funding for applications for funding to the municipalities, which should specifically be used to apply for funding to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
While regulations are easily the target of criticism in the Member States, some experts believe that the EU's efforts to regulate, and thus also to make the European Union as a whole more effective and develop, deserve more recognition.
In the opinion of these experts, a more serious problem is the EU funding for projects which have nothing in common with the deepening of European integration, but which were forced by individual Member States during the budgetary negotiations.
Emotions in this country also arise from the fact that the Czech Republic, like other Member States in Brussels, has to fight for the right to use specific names of traditional products and does not always win this battle.
After a six-year struggle with Germany and Austria, the Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvar
The term rum may only be used for sugar cane distillate products, not sugar beet products.
The official list of products registered in the EU now includes the Karlovy Vary Zwieback, Carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, or the Saaz hops, in the company of the world famous Feta and Gorgonzola cheeses, the Lübeck marzipan or Parma ham.
The Pardubic gingerbread or Hořic rolls can boast with an EU mark.
