The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in the mind - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I think the building is funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large-scale operation, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder what we need a library for today.
Everyone has internet, iPad and e-books.
No one's going to one of those old-style libraries on their own today, is he?
Spijkenisse, a sleep city that is hardly in need of a visit at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands as a whole.
In order to counter this stupid circumstance, a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro notes as beautifully pinned reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library had to be here!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural office MVRDV, master of the ludicrous bar charts and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with familiar serenity and appeared for the competition hearing anno 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin in his face.
And while the jury was still looking around and twitching with the armpits, the cheeky Maas piled up his exquisite souvenirs in size to a pyramid and ended his action-based speech with the words: "Dear municipality!"
So this is my proposal for the Buchenberg of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is piled up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This makes the faceless small town retort, which so far had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunnedly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
But above all Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: Bookeldorado under cheese bell.
There is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the real room and reading pleasures open up during the walking climb of the topography.
The all-round glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights clearly speak the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally, the bookshelves stand along the façade, and in the middle lies a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and put the reading area inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology center.
A special pleasure are the black bookcases, which are wall coverings, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase railings.
Optics, haptics and smell are foreign.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake the head of the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, on request from the standard.
And so one day, in a farm in Frisia, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years in the Netherlands a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in greenhouses and in fields.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, for the first time in these quantities, the fleece was pressed into plates four centimetres thick.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-capable material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you have reached the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-meter-long hike, the Literaturcafé not only rewards you with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and stuffed ficus trees.
They provide an atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology," Trouborst says.
It is heated and cooled with geothermal energy.
Although the Bücherberg stands under a glass fall, the sun shines only briefly inside even on sunny days.
The wide wooden glue ties, which stand across the glass facade, serve as shading and capture a large part of the solar radiation.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already ventured the way into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls Boekenberg Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal holdings.
This is intended for the first time to fill the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has worked out.
The shelves are filled up to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just a decorative thing.
Thus, MVRDV has succeeded in the supreme discipline, which is called the identity foundation in the specialist jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in US-European relations, Berlin thus balances on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signalled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy managed, so to speak, by the US, towards a German foreign policy.
In addition, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still touching on their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like France or Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, into the head in the Arab countries.
That definitely matters.
But I wouldn't want to give it too much weight either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it definitely plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect for itself.
After all, it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly declared itself in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic politics, these differences have always existed.
I believe that Obama’s government secretly has a lot of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is currently not the case.
So they can't be part of a broader line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, because of its relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that it is clear to the Germans that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or is Germany still struggling to lead?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a larger role, various anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be receptive to a wide range of neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European politics is steadily decreasing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, who else is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, they don't like it and make it even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to address the challenges of the transatlantic community.
