Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomaviruses, herpes genitalis or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabies belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and Trippers are especially common among men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four of the five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungal), gonorrhea and human papillomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - yet this group accounts for about 20 percent of new HIV infections.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged between 15 and 25 years.
Human papillomaviruses are also common in adolescents in this country.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has decreased since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2700 cases.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms indicate venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, lower abdominal pain as well as vesicles or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
In part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubricating infections and close body contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially for frequently changing sex partners.
Diagnosed early, most STIs can be cured and late consequences avoided.
