Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the worst smelling fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living - not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country’s secret of success have something to do with the local appetite for rather smelly fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
You put them in the middle of a pile of dirty, wet sportswear.
And leave her there for a week.
So about this one has to imagine the nasal stunning smell of Rakfisk, one of the great delicacies of Norway.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There are snow, spectacular landscapes - and this persistent smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is salted trout, which is fermented in water for up to a year, depending on how stinking you would like to have your fish.
When the darkness comes across the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, dedicated to this, well, very impressive specialty.
