But it is precisely this, according to the family, that she has been denied until now.
The authorities treated me like I was a chatterer, a troublemaker, a snitch.
They want their verdict simply to be accepted and kept quiet.
"But this is not possible if there were so many formal errors and omissions," she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential bond on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take particular care of this problem during his term in office.
"I hope that as President he is as he was as Governor," says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
The prosecutor claims that Bradley Manning did not complain about abuse
The prosecutor's office contradicts Bradley Manning's allegations that he was mistreated in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defence seeks to dismiss the prosecution on the grounds of too harsh conditions of detention
The Private of the U.S. Army is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The prosecutor's office tried to find out on Friday that the Army Private Bradley Manning - charged with the greatest disclosure of confidential information in American history - missed several occasions to complain about the allegedly suffered abuse in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Mannings during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that documents relating to weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month term in Quantico, Virginia did not have any complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the prosecution - Manning had already been adequately punished by the hard time in prison - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as a source of information.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officers had filled out after meeting Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been serving from July 2010 to April 2011 under increased conditions of detention.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards to be "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole to be "very professional".
According to Fein, the forms did not contain any complaints about abuse, although officers had asked Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they had to deal with them, but that they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down "no problems" (after discussing the concerns), and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything," says Manning.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to have his observation status downgraded to "prevention of injuries".
The military claimed that it had assigned this restrictive status - one level below the suicide risk - to its protection and to the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and to get rid of the observation status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," said Manning.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that in Kuwait he had considered suicide and had passed out due to the heat.
Not being allowed to know what was happening to him or to the outside world was a burden.
"My world shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said that he had tried to keep moving, because by day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards couldn't see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to the treatment of Manning.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas Military Prison.
On Friday, Judge Manning also asked about an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep one night naked in his cell in Quantico and have to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
During the interview on Friday, Manning claimed that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night. He had previously tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning had told the officer that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experiences and drastically reduce his prison sentence if he is convicted at his trial in the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offences, while other charges, which are considered too extreme, are to be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all of the highest security precautions in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence on the Internet, transmission of national defence information and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he is threatened with life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to accuse the emigrants - they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when perplexity spread in me.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), the other for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, uncertain to which I should go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called Mexicans all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York "Italian".
Later, I chose "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's home there was no need for shortcuts or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least well enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I don't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet President Obama.
The agenda included all the issues you would expect when the heads of these two countries met: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to stay in Mexico instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue the war of Mexico against the drug cartels, even if he did not give any details.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought about the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the country's leaders to leave more than half of their territory to them, with a gun held in their hands.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event cannot be overlooked.
So, as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the mildest criticism of Mexico, one hears complaints - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - about how the Americans oppress the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma go on the war path.
Yet Mexico’s greatest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person - perhaps a parent or grandparents - was offered no chance in Mexico and emigrated north.
And in most cases this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our faithfulness is to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may have now lived the American dream, attended good schools and got good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream that we live - not the Mexican dream.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This is clearly true of the United States.
We are also aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial of humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our gang to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn't see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is tension between Mexicans and Mexican Americans, because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans resent them.
While she is an American citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they are neither part of the country nor of the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we're seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary "ambassadors" for Mexico, who represent their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great it is to visit this country and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And in view of the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure whether this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through this alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge about how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more Mexican than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected cornerstone of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual debt assignments, countless buildings were laid in ruins, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed - and for the first time rockets from Gaza have been struck near the Israeli metropolis Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems far from appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, this week's fighting has strengthened the hard-boiled on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has been controlling the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though its group itself has suffered great losses.
Although several Hamas leaders have been killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are being impounded in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has not yet succeeded in destroying Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And Hamas leaders might conclude that they have the time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a resurgent, regional power once regarded as Israel's closest Muslim ally, has taken on the Hamas side - just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Celebrating Hamas supporters believe that there is an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where the militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist character could face the fall of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And especially the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - by far the most populous and important Arab country - on the southern flank of Israel has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his downfall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is closely associated with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that even Israel and the United States cannot push out.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
Militaryly, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli anti-missile system, "Iron Dome," has proved its worth and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
For at least a while Israel will be able to sleep calmly.
In diplomatic terms, the United States remains steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalation of violence.
Israel has been doing well in recent years, particularly under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free from suicide bombers, not least thanks to the blockades that have led to the West Bank and thus to the major part of a possible Palestinian state, which protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared illegal under international law, but are being further developed.
Netanyahu is in good shape. His Likud party joined an even more militant group under Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 elections.
Why do these deceitful Palestinians also coddle and leave them with their own state?
If they really had control of the West Bank, would they not, like their fellow Gazans, fire missiles?
No, it's better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to lift their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab spring could make a dash for them.
Even if the Islamists, who are now in power in Egypt and in other countries, have little left for Israel, they will first focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economies.
The fact that pragmatic President Morsi and Barack Obama joined forces to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign - and perhaps symbolise the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more in the long term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratisation, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to repress Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take its diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The right answer is that represented by the more rational representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states where Israel is ceding territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, now has to stop arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by an exchange of territories and a common Jerusalem.
Outside Arab nations should also encourage Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must play its part in encouraging Israel to negotiate.
During his first term in office, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the white house, it seems as if he is also averse to participation.
But that is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has an essential interest in a stable Middle East.
And this includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian legislation on uniform cigarette packaging enters into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral, olive green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, is from Saturday.
Australia is thus introducing the world's most stringent regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to discourage young people from smoking by removing the glamorous image of tobacco consumption.
This is based on studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at 26 will not start smoking with 99% probability even after that.
"You can already see in children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," says Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek. She quotes studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws favoured the black market trade, resulting in cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the unbearable packaging has increased enormously since the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco companies failed two months ago at the Australian Supreme Court to challenge the laws.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale businesses and is waiting for new stocks.
It's a good deal for us.
According to experts, the catch lies in the popularity of social media with exactly the population group to which the plan is addressed.
A number of Australian laws have banished tobacco companies from TV advertising, barred them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most traders to stop interpreting cigarettes in stores. Now, tobacco advertising has switched to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned Internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
"Anyone who markets tobacco and has only a small area left to advertise their products cannot get around the Internet," says Becky Freeman, a healthcare researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has noticed an increase in experience reports on brands written by "normal people."
One has to ask oneself the question: Is this just a private person who finds so much pleasure in marlboro cigarettes that she even records a video for it - or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of marketing, industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay the Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules - those countries complain to the World Trade Organisation about unfair trade restrictions, although none of the countries is doing major trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to issue photographic warnings in 2001.
These have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Harder laws are being considered in Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures don't affect me.
I'm just ignoring her.
"You just take a tilt and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box with a photo printed with a mouth tumor.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd stop, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the tobacco trade "King of the Pack" in downtown Sydney, says the uniform packaging has made filling up of its shelves more difficult.
"It used to take me an hour to sort in a delivery, now I need four," Yu says.
"The government should have simply banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said okay, that's it, we'll close up," he adds visibly furiously.
