And because most of us are almost constantly staring at one or the other screen these days, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
Should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that one more time.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011), does not see it that way.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
The walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti over boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "doing a satisfactory job but not being able to do it".
Boredom is therefore different from apathy in that the person is not busy but wants to be.
In apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a "disturbing of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly".
Boredom can almost sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored persons see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed persons see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Boredom under the Aspects of Attention", which appeared in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a band on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighbouring room, which had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they were more bored than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, could not find any reason for them and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or exhausting task can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, Associate Professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
If, on the other hand, one engages in monotonous activity - "just like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help to not feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that scribbling and scribbling, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even combat it by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to play around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a booming loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
In order to measure these differences, researchers developed in the 1980s a "scale for susceptibility to boredom".
On the scale, there are statements like "Many things I have to do, repeat themselves and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything."
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys get bored more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - especially as regards the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a rather tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents with a pager seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored at school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were not at school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Today, 21 years later, Professor Larson says he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is certain that "young people are felt to be particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their daily routine.
So back to my question of origin: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall prey to gambling or drugs in order to alleviate them - this has been shown by studies.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors investigate the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do best right now.
If you're bored and you use this energy to play the guitar and cook, you'll be happy.
But while television can provide happiness in the short term, it can evaporate in the long term.
So if you're going to give your bored child an iPad, you can stop it from boredom. However, it didn't learn to entertain or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control is transferred from one situation to the other."
The child not only learns to talk, but also gets more self - control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of them.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant flow of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we often have to be bored, but boredom is the agonizing, constant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth people are only looking for a way to switch off and relax.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to deal with once the noise has stopped."
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
The 19-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco stands for a crime in the southeast of Colorado that will soon be legal in this state: the possession of a few marijuana chunks and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police found marijuana in the car, Orozco was subpoenaed for possession of drugs and drug supplies - cavalier's crimes, each with a fine of $100 - and received a court appointment.
"We are treated like criminals," Orozco says.
But is he one?
In the uncertain weeks after the state's decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for its own use, the response to hundreds of minor drug offences depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of misdemeanours dealing with marijuana are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
The police authorities no longer persecute adults over 21 years of age for small possessions. This is permitted by law as soon as the new laws enter into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative counties of Colorado have announced that they will continue to prosecute and still quote people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their communities.
"This situation is developing so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next," says Daniel J. Oates, Chief of Police in Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, production, distribution and sale of the drug, with a deadline of 1 December 2013.
In Washington, Colorado is, in any case, ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, where the drug was legalized for medical purposes and then for personal consumption.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well-suited for guidance," says Brian E. Smith, Spokesman of the Spirits Authority in Washington State.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
"We don't have a real precedent to follow," he adds.
The Washington Act, called I-502, enters into force on December 6, and thus also constitutes the end point of a grey zone in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but the property is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified during this time - for example, how to agree on the government's "reasonable access" to licensed marijuana with the ban on cannabis shops within 300 metres of schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
"Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area," says Ben Livingston, spokesperson for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21st, Chief Oates sent an email to his staff in Aurora saying that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana crimes in people over 21 years of age, and that the police would "as of now" not seek criminal charges for these crimes.
Chief Oates added that the police would continue to enforce urban regulations to regulate medical marijuana growers and continue to persecute drug traffickers.
In Weld County, North Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck holds a stricter view.
After the vote, he stated that his authority would continue to prosecute cases of marijuana possession, mainly to get consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people have to answer for the possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have also been charged with other crimes.
"Our authority has a duty to prosecute offences that were committed at the time of the crime," Buck stated in a statement.
The reactions are ambivalent even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
The police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, no longer show adults for the possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending property proceedings.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time trying to enforce the law until it changes," he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the very beginning that it would not be easy to reconcile the personal use of marijuana with the complexities of government and the legal system.
And the contradictory reactions across the state brought a profound dissension among local officials with regard to the great green experiment.
District prosecutors are a "cultural barrier," says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents defendants in court for marijuana crimes and acts as a local spokesperson for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
"They have spent such a large part of their lives prosecuting people for the fact that they still cannot accept legalisation," he believes.
The first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol are Colorado and Washington as national models for legalizing drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an age of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at federal level as a criminal offence.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will give in.
Despite several sensational arrests of medical marijuana consumers and sellers, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy advisor to the Obama administration, believes that although criminal officers will probably not enter doors to confiscate smaller amounts of drugs, they will probably be reluctant to tolerate the legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local community administrations approved moratoria for new marijuana businesses, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, decided on a six-month ban that would probably be passed next week.
"We don't want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at federal level," says Bob Nicholson, a member of the City Council.
Our community voted against this amendment to the law.
We depend on what the community has chosen and not on what the state has chosen.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I am Tory
Not only university students today are attacked for their views
It had always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended the university that I once thought was the greatest temple of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposion that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my arrival at Worscester College at the end of the eighties - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my suitcases again and thus caused the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed into tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighboring room.
The author A N Wilson shamily declared that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I had come from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason - a reason that seemed all the more narrow and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: my father Woodrow Wyatt, who had since died, had been an important advisor to Margaret Thatcher and I support the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate right students is suffering similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for the same equality protection that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior Common Room (JCR) of Corpus Christi College state that they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable" because of their political views.
They call for a place on the equal rights committee of their college to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Her situation was aggravated by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the University of Oxford's Conservative Student Association, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and flaunted with a silver suit and a silver-set walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are regarded as "sin rams for the introduction of higher tuition fees".
20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the Conservative Students' Association of Nottingham University, said in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing trend towards the left in universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other."
Samuel Roberts, 21 and a history student in Corpus Christi, who initiated the application for greater protection, believes that such a climate is "unpleasant." 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-designate of the Conservative Student Association of Oxford, says she has observed a growing rejection of moderate right students among JCR members.
"This poses a danger to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members," she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I had arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university had voted not to award Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an honorary title due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have made even Stalinists startle.
In the first days of the first semester week, during which new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a foretaste of the future events.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even gladly took part in it.
Political issues such as the miners' strike, privatisation and the government's rejection of sanctions against South Africa's apartheid regime found their way into the wood-paneled rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate 18th-century French texts into English. I had not been prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said the tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and pretty ugly.
"Do Thatcher followers want to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students giggled.
In my eyes, tears were coming up.
"I suggest you take a few French lessons in your spare time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt growled at me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That night, I was sitting alone in college at dinner when someone tipped me on the shoulder.
It was an English student from the second year named James who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it's the way it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory will be harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory first-semesters pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub, I later tried to pretend.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who ironically attended Eton College, which was considered conservative, said to me, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one of them asked me.
They beat each other, don't they?
I felt as homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever manage to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I have to turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay ahead of me extended before my spiritual eye to a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as Tory was Norman Stone, professor of contemporary history, who was based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also because he had advised Thatcher on foreign policy and written speeches for them.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty and rejected it for his Marxist-deterministic historical perspective.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I started commuting between Oxford and my parents' house and found refuge with more open - minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said.
They would never do anything like that, not in my city of dreamy spires.
Even my Communist friends always showed impeccable manners.
His wet eyes were clouding.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure you're just being teased.
It would break my heart if you left.
Tired by my frequent travels to London, my emotional resistance became weaker.
One of my male friends, also Tory's followers, had yielded to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, during which another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Although I secretly fell into shame, I admitted that my parents had given me a "brainwash" and called it "old fools."
The relief lasted only a short time.
It was my father who hit the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my rabbits gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You're welcome to call me a whiny wimp.
But no 18-year-old should ever suffer such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford - a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
