The advertising company BBH, which shot the video, keeps the hope that the commercial will reach in a fun way to draw attention to the problem.
Her creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says that he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill their "national duty."
This is something just for the internet, so we had to make it funny and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world when it comes to planting, so we realized that it was a subject that we had to take care of.
We knew that the government had tried a lot, such as the marketing of perfume with pheromones or the organization of speed dating evenings (fast flirts).
It is possible that many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought, why don't we make something as creative as possible to address this problem, such as composing a rap?
1.2 Children
Those who do not take this issue lightly are the government of Singapore.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was over 2 - which is also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't the Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy of the National Population Authority, says that this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has made it possible for people to have much more options in terms of life goals and priorities besides getting married and making a family," she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of singles and to the delay in marriage and births, the result of which is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration in order to counteract the reduction of the population has led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the barely concealed xenophobia against many new immigrants is flourishing, especially against the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the Singapore ruling party has achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs, and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
It has already had an impact on the housing market.
The Department of Urban Development has begun to monitor the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that may be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living space of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the lifestyle of the single person and that they deter construction companies from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger units.
This means that they are much better for our cash flow.
He admits, however, that the new standards provide clearer orientations for developers who have previously been hindered if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, the talks with Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will not have much impact.
"People are stressed out, homes and education are expensive, which is why many put it off," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It is important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women cite their careers, the stress and the cost of property and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That is why the Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children - there is still so much the government can do.
The offline private offline is online private
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "the area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference".
What's private for someone under the age of 16?
How is this definition applied to its everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he exposes himself to when he exposes situations on the Internet that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who are often on the Internet.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "something very personal" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when they applied it to social networks.
"I wouldn't reveal my deepest secrets in a post," says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the meaning of "private" in websites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I'm also spending my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that isn't mine, or someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, nudes, crimes, or to write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge assures us that he knows 35 friends he has in FB and nine in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone will answer me, I'll just upload them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can talk quickly to relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
When asked, he answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone recommends a stranger to him, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask he admits not to know 20 of the people he added to his friend list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to the boy, no one has hinted to him or asked him for his address or telephone number.
"If someone pushes me or demands it from me, I simply remove it from my account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unknown to experiences known today as cyberbullying.
A friend's friend was blackmailed into a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who did it," he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the account.
"He just did it privately."
He then explains a number of steps to securely configure a user account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, that's what I'd do if I didn't like him or if I wanted to wipe him out.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to orient the children and young people, it is necessary to understand that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for the search for information; however, with the appearance of these pages, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's degree in pedagogy at Yale University, and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants", shaped these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach them when we are still learning ourselves," he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue, "because we require them to have a defined criterion on what can be disseminated, published or said, at an age where maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be selective when it is important to them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and young people what privacy is is to ask them questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then mentions some possibilities: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger. Then why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like to have a photo of you published, like the one you published from a friend?
Do you know what the others are publishing about you?
Did you ask permission from the other people when you labeled photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Do everyone need to know what you're doing at any moment?
Another point is to give them understanding that they need to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educator consultant, comments that it is essential for parents to read through the guidelines of social networks carefully.
When they understand all the sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "You shall not speak to strangers".
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was to be signed theoretically by the seven governments present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the exam, but then stated that it would be published at some time on the Peruvian government's website.
On questions relating to the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day in the press room only the picture of the presidential meeting was transmitted without sound with the message "private meeting, limited audio".
The few information circulating among journalists was received from the press representatives of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, causing discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the presidential office of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the Humala Declaration and not the official document for the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South America - Arab States (ASPA) Summit, and on this occasion, despite the press's strong request, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published either.
On the official ASPA website, you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems for journalists were in place, but to a large extent they restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice which resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICJ, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the trial that Lima initiated against Santiago, to hear the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences that we are currently presenting to this International Court of Justice," said Humala along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts," adds Piñera and greeted Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
Both presidents confirmed that they would submit to the ICJ after Colombia filed a complaint against the Bogotá Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this International Court of Justice.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 following the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after lunch in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, in which it announced that 16 decisions were taken and that the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment of 17 billion dollars.
Regarding the decisions taken, he said that the Unasur countries "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we will extend the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, and to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America, and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant traits, but rather serve to expand our production capacity and to show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects designed to improve spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas...and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a read-out statement.
Among these projects would be five Peruvians, who would be on the cross-axis of their territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which would provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations" from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he was expecting a meeting with his counterpart in Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico, in order to treat the maritime conflict respectfully according to a judgment called into question by Bogotá.
"Maybe I'll meet President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also requires talks with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilised and respectfully as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the new President of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the Defence Ministers of the Block also met in advance to adopt the action plan for 2013, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is presided over by the regional bloc.
"South America must learn to integrate its citizens," says Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, today confirmed that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal, whereby "South America can actually learn something from Europe."
Correa, who attended the 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which took place in Lima, told state television in Peru that Europeans "killed themselves in World War II and other conflicts" and "are now practically a fatherland."
In this sense, he defended the project of creating a South American citizenship that would drive the member states of Unasur forward.
"The free movement of citizens and workers in all South American countries, as is already the case in the Andean Community, must be achieved; however, there are still reactionary sectors that seek a return to the past," he warned.
The President of Ecuador also supported the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OEA) with the aim of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those who have signed the San José Convention on Human Rights.
Those who teach never commit to anything, and in return we always sign everything to the South Americans.
