"That would affect everyone's health," he added.
Correa stated that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange at the Embassy of Ecuador in London since June was the granting of a free letter allowing him to travel to Ecuador, and that this would be in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe. He stressed that there had been talks with London to find a solution for the imprisoned founder of WikiLeaks.
We are not dealing with human rights, we are not using this word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe, because the lawyer of Assange, Baltazar Garzón, conducts a series of proceedings at various European authorities," he said.
And "if Britain grants this leave tomorrow, I think it's done."
And when Sweden interrogated Mr Assange at the Ecuadorian Embassy in London or via Skype, as Swedish case law allows and has done in other cases, the problem is over.
Correa took the opportunity to confirm himself as a defender of freedom of the press and said that what he did not tolerate were "the mediocrity, the evil intention, and the lie that invalidated freedom of expression."
"The greatest enemies of freedom of the press are not the evil and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who seek and extort profit," he said.
In this sense, he congratulated himself that Ecuador would no longer be dominated by such journalists "and would not be dominated by bankers or hegemonic and bourgeois countries," and anticipated that in a re-election he "will deepen the revolution in order to continue the path in this right direction."
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in Unasur at least until his next elections, arguing that the organism "must remain hard and not allow any opportunistism and no coup d'état disguised as legal" because it "destructed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay."
Moreover, the President of Ecuador considers the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, now and after the judgment of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, that favored the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime borders between the two countries, "absolutely entitled."
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in pursuit of a common path.
They must be comprehensively treated so that they can be overcome and looked ahead.
He also trusted in a good settlement of disputes over the sea borders between Peru and Chile before the same court, saying that "it is right for Latin America to call international authorities if both countries commit themselves to accept the verdict, even if it is very harsh."
With regard to the possibility that he would stand as a candidate for the next presidential election in Ecuador in order to achieve his third mandate in a row, he stated that he sees this possibility "with much optimism and joy, although sometimes it is also very difficult."
Correa stated that if he lost the February 2013 elections, he would withdraw from political life.
Power has never interested me personally, but under such unjust circumstances as Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement had the belief that it was I who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to shoulder this responsibility," he said.
If I were to win, it would be my last period as president, after which I retire from public life.
This also applies if we lose.
"That's decided," he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the President of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I have just spoken to the Vice-President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, who told me that he travelled there for a planned, routine treatment, and that he would be expected to return to Cuba after the election campaign.
"In no case does it mean a relapse in the state of health of President Chávez," he commented.
